# 8 elements (or steps) for policy innovation

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Overview
The 8 Elements for Policy Innovation is a design thinking-inspired approach specifically focused on public policy planning and system mapping.

## Purpose
This tool is used in R&amp;D to systematically approach complex policy problems, gain a deep understanding of the system and stakeholders involved, reframe the problem, explore innovative solutions, test and refine policy ideas, and implement and monitor policies effectively.

## How it works
The 8 Elements for Policy Innovation consists of 8 key steps: 
1) Policy Journey Exploration, 
2) Systems Mapping, 
3) Intent Development &amp; Problem Reframing, 
4) System Transformation Review, 
5) Solution &amp; Policy Ideation, 
6) Policy Assessment, Testing &amp; Experimentation, 
7) Execution Planning and Policy Implementation, and 
8) Policy Monitoring and Evaluation.

## Requirements
A collaborative effort from diverse stakeholders, systems thinking and design thinking skills, a deep understanding of the policy context and problem, openness to innovative ideas and experimentation, and resources for testing and implementing policy are required.

## Reflections
Ensure inclusive participation of diverse stakeholders, be open to reframing the problem based on new insights, prioritize actionable and impactful leverage points in the system, thoroughly test and refine policy ideas before full-scale implementation, and continuously monitor and adapt policies based on feedback and outcomes.

## Related methods (if any)
Design Thinking, System Thinking

## License
Free or open

## Examples
The Thailand Policy Lab has used this tool to develop innovative public policies.
